<h2>
Introduction:</h2>
This lab examines and lists the local integer and floating point environments
with respect to limits on <i>csci</i> (a <b>Sparc</b> architecture) and
compares them with those on the authors' machine and on an <b>Intel</b>
architecture.
<h2>
Lab Assignment:</h2>

<ol>
<ol>
<li>
Create a new directory, <i>lab3</i>, and move to it.</li>

<li> <i>run</i>: <tt><b>cp</b> ~aanda/cs201/source/CHAppndx/PE-0[12].c++ .</tt>
<font color="red">{dot}</font></li>
<li> <i>run</i>: <tt><b>cp</b> ~aanda/cs201/source/CHAppndx/PE-0[12].Intel .</tt>
<font color="red">{dot}</font></li>

<li> <i>compile</i>: <tt>g++ PE-01.c++ -o PE-01.exe</tt> </li>
<li> <i>compile</i>: <tt>g++ PE-02.c++ -o PE-02.exe</tt> </li>

<li>

<li> <i>Run</i>: each executable {<i>*.exe</i>}</li> saving the output in PE-01.Sparc and PE-02.Sparc respectively.

<li> <i>Copy</i>: each source file naming the copy PE-01.Author and PE-02.Author respectively</li>

<li> <i>Edit</i>: each *.Author file so that it only contains the Authors' machine's output without any comment tokens</li>

<li> <i>Copy</i>: each *.Author file to a new file with a *.Table suffix</li>

<li> <i>Edit</i>: each *.Table file to have three columns, where each column contains the output for that row for the three different architectures.  Add your <u>name</u> and <u>today's date</u> to the top of the file with a line of underscore characters underneath as a separator.</li>

<li>
<i>Print</i> two copies of the *.Table files together using <b>lpr -# 2</b> <i>outputfilename</i>.</li>


<li>
Hand in one printout.</li>

<li>
Retain one printout for your notes.</li>
</ol>
</ol>

<h4>
Editing Suggestions:</h4>

<li>
run <b>vim</b></li>

<li>
set the following flags:</li>

<blockquote>
<li>
"<tt>:set cin sw=4</tt>"  {this maintains indenting.
See p. 206 of our Unix text for details}</li>

<li>
"<tt>:syntax enable</tt>"
{provides automatic syntax highlighting to help illuminate structure and
mistakes}</li>

<li>
"yank" and "put" similar lines to save editing work {<b>yy</b> and
<b>p</b> commands}</li>
</blockquote>

<li>
use two terminal windows Write from the editor periodically {"<b>:w</b>"}
while compiling and running in the other window to catch syntax and other
errors early.</li>

